The paper deals with the problem of finding a total dominating set of minimum size in graphs, which is a classic problem in graph theory and falls under the category of computational complexity and algorithms. The paper specifically focuses on planar graphs, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also mentions the use of reduction rules and kernelization, which are common techniques in parameterized complexity (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the concept of genus, which is a topological property of graphs and may suggest that it belongs to the sub-category of graph theory (cs.GT). Additionally, the paper deals with domination problems, which are often studied in the sub-category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and computational complexity (cs.CC).
